n in Clemens Meyer’s Als wir träumten -- tPart IV: Literary Generations — Competing Perspectives -- t9: Autobiographical Writing in Three Generations of a GDR Family: Christa Wolf — Annette Simon — Jana Simon -- t10: Accursed Progenitors? Extending the Generation-Gap Debate to GDR Parents -- t11: Parallels and Divergences in Post-1989 Memory Discourse: A Comparative Review of the Slovak Experience -- tPart V: Afterlives -- t12: Dances of Death: A Last Literature from the GDR -- t13: “Die Gegenwart war es nicht”: Irina Liebmann and the Post-Wende Uncanny -- t14: One Iota of Difference: Remembering GDR Literature as Socialist Literature -- tNotes on the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNew essays on the evolution of cultural memory of the former German Democratic Republic since 1989-90 and its importance for Germany's continuing unification process.Twenty years on from the dramatic events that led to the opening of the Berlin Wall and the collapse of the GDR, the subjective dimension of German unification is still far from complete. The nature of the East German state remains a matter of cultural as well as political debate. This volume of new research focuses on competing memories of the GDR and the ways they have evolved in the mass media, literature, and film since 1989-90. Taking as its point ofdeparture the impact of iconic visual images of the fall of the Wall on our understanding of the historical GDR, the volume first considers the decade of cultural conflict that followed unification and then the emergence of a morecomplex and diverse "textual memory" of the GDR since the Berlin Republic was established in 1999. It highlights competing generational perspectives on the GDR era and the unexpected "afterlife" of the GDR in recent publications.The volume as a whole shows the vitality of eastern German culture two decades after the demise of the GDR and the centrality of these memory debates to the success of Germany's unification process. Contributors: Daniel Argelès, Stephen Brockmann, Arne De Winde, Wolfgang Emmerich, Andrea Geier, Hilde Hoffmann, Astrid Köhler, Karen Leeder, Andrew Plowman, Gillian Pye, Benjamin Robinson, Catherine Smale, Rosemary Stott, Dennis Tate, Frederik VanDam, Nadezda Zemaníková. Renate Rechtien is Lecturer in German Studies, and Dennis Tate is Emeritus Professor of German Studies, both at the University of Bath, UK.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCollective memoryxGermany. 0aGerman prose literaturexHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aGerman prose literaturexHistory and criticismx21st century. 0aLiterature and historyxHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aLiterature and historyxHistoryx21st centuryxGermany. 0aPopular culturexGermany. 4aFilm & Theatre. 4aGerman Literature. 4aModern History. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aBerlin Wall.  aGDR.  aGerman unification.  aafterlife of the GDR.  acultural conflict.  acultural memory.  afilm.  agenerational perspectives.  aiconic visual images.  aliterature.  amass media.  atextual memory.1 aArgeles, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArgelès, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrockmann, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Winde, Arne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmmerich, Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeier, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoffmann, Hilde, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoehler, Astrid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.go